tested as well , e . g . flat packs and dual in - line packages ( dip ). it is known as well to mount semiconductor chips directly to a printed circuit board , and it can be appreciated that individual semiconductor chips or chip carriers of a particularly complex design might be tested individually . parallel or simultaneous testing is accomplished by providing multiple , substantially part of a model 9622 receiver . each sensing circuit further includes a high voltage terminal 56 connected to power supply 28 such that it is biased to a predetermined high voltage , e . g . + 5 volts . high voltage terminal 56 is connected to a common terminal or node 58 through an input resistor 60 . node 58 provides a voltage level , in this case a positive voltage of less than 5 , to the positive input terminal of differential amplifier 62 , and also to a terminal 64 connected to the input of the circuit under test . the output voltage of the circuit under test is provided to a terminal 66 of the sensing circuit , whereby the output voltage is provided through a common terminal or node 68 to the inversion input of differential amplifier 62 ( preferably with good common mode rejection ), and also to ground through an output resistor 70 . it should be noted that the terms &# 34 ; input &# 34 ; and &# 34 ; output &# 34 ; for resistors 60 and 70 are used for convenience . these resistors can , as well , be considered as connected to the outputs of the test circuit and providing the inputs to amplifier 62 . in effect , input resistor 60 , output resistor 70 and the arrangement of the circuit under test and differential amplifier 62 in parallel are combined to provide three resistances in series between high voltage terminal 56 and a low voltage terminal 72 , i . e . ground . the sensing of open or unacceptably resistive test circuits is based upon the difference in voltage at the positive and inversion terminals of the differential amplifier . the differential amplifier is a known logic or digital device which generates one of two alternative logic states : a &# 34 ; high &# 34 ; state or higher voltage output whenever the voltage at the positive terminal exceeds the voltage at the inversion terminal by a characteristic or predetermined threshold ; and a low logical output of voltage whenever the voltage at the positive input does not exceed the voltage at the inversion input by the threshold . differential amplifier 62 is selected for its predetermined threshold voltage level , e . g . approximately 1 . 5 volts . an open or unacceptably resistive test circuit is detected as follows . amplifier 62 is a high resistance or impedance device , such that the resistance of its parallel arrangement with the test circuit essentially equals the resistance of the test circuit itself , a nominal or expected resistance of about 2 ohms . input and output resistors 60 and 70 have a substantially greater resistance , for example 100 ohms each . consequently the voltage drop across the test circuit , i . e . across the comparator inputs , is quite small compared to the voltage drop across each of the resistors , for example less than 0 . 1 volts . thus , when the test circuit provides a short or closed path , the drop in voltage between the comparator inputs is much smaller than the 1 . 5 volt threshold and differential amplifier 62 generates the low logic state . conversely , when the test circuit is open the resistance of the parallel arrangement is many times that of resistors 60 and 70 , to the point where the voltage difference between the comparator inputs exceeds the threshold voltage and causes amplifier 62 to generate the high logic state . amplifier 62 also generates the high logic state when the resistance of the circuit being tested is higher than an acceptable maximum corresponding to the predetermined voltage threshold . in particular , given the threshold of 1 . 5 volts in combination with input and output resistors of 100 ohms , and further assuming that the resistance of amplifier 62 is such that the resistance of the above - discussed parallel combination is essentially equal to the resistance of the test circuit , then a resistance in the test circuit of about 70 ohms or greater will cause amplifier 62 to fire . in practice , the actual threshold voltage may vary , for example between 1 . 2 volts and 1 . 8 volts . such deviation , however , does not interfere with the identification of open circuits in any material respect , since the nominal resistance of the circuits is substantially lower than that required to trigger amplifier 62 , while the resistance of an open circuit is of course substantially higher . the output of all sensing circuits 54 is thus a digital word indicating the conditions of the test circuits . amplifier 62 can be provided with a hysteresis ( positive feedback ) loop with a resistance if desired . this would result in cleaner switching output signals , but also would reduce sensitivity . on occasion , it is desirable in the course of testing to configure sensing circuit 54 to provide a logic state indicating normal operation , in spite of the fact that the circuit under test is open or of a high resistance . this option is provided as nand gate 74 receiving the output of differential amplifier 62 , and with another input connected to high voltage terminal 56 through a resistor 76 of a high resistance , e . g . 10 , 000 ohms . a shunt 78 connects resistor 76 to ground through a switch 80 which normally is open . with switch 80 open , a high input is provided to nand gate 74 . a high input to the nand gate from amplifier 62 as well will generate a logic low output from nand gate 74 , indicating an error condition such as an open circuit . of course , for a closed or short circuit the output of differential amplifier 62 is low and the output of nand gate 74 is high , indicating the normal operating condition . if switch 80 is closed , a low logic state is provided as an input to nand gate 74 , resulting in a high or normal condition output regardless of the input received from the differential amplifier . in short , once an error condition is identified for a particular test circuit , switch 80 can be closed to override the error output . in the multiple circuit arrangement the resistances of input and output resistors 60 and 70 , for example increasing sensitivity to generate the error logic state at a lower resistance value by substituting input and output resistors # Ressign the labels in filtered_dataset to align with a new ClassLabel feature containing only the top labels, with the label indices updated accordingly.
# I want to work with a reduced set of labels and ensure that they have a consistent and clear indexing scheme.

from datasets import ClassLabel

# Create a new ClassLabel feature with only the top labels
new_labels = ClassLabel(names=top_labels)
# A dictionary new_label_map is created to map the original label IDs (old_ids) from filtered_dataset to new label IDs (new_ids) within the range of the top labels.
# This dictionary comprehension iterates over top_label_ids and assigns each old label ID to a new label ID that corresponds to its index in top_labels.
new_label_map = {old_id: new_labels.str2int(new_labels.int2str(new_id)) for new_id, old_id in enumerate(top_label_ids)}

# The remap_label function updates each example in filtered_dataset by replacing its label with the new mapped label ID from new_label_map.
def remap_label(example):
    example['label'] = new_label_map[example['label']]
    return example

# Transform filtered_dataset into remapped_dataset, where labels are now indexed according to the new ClassLabel mapping.
remapped_dataset = filtered_dataset.map(remap_label)

# Cast the label column in remapped_dataset to the newly created new_labels feature,
# ensuring the dataset's label column has the correct, updated mapping with only the top labels.
remapped_dataset = remapped_dataset.cast_column('label', new_labels)

def compute_metrics(pred):
    """
    Calcualtes accuracy and f1 score given predictions.

    Args:
        pred (EvalPrediction):
    """
    labels = pred.label_ids
    preds = pred.predictions.argmax(-1)
    f1 = f1_score(labels, preds, average="weighted")
    acc = accuracy_score(labels, preds)
    return {"accuracy": acc, "f1": f1}

Method 2: Fine-tune a transformer model by segmenting the text such that it fits within the context window of the model.¶

The segmentation approach processes long text sequences by breaking them into smaller chunks that fit within the model's context window¶

In [49]:
# text.split() splits the text into individual words.
# The for loop iterates over words in steps of max_length, creating chunks of words that each have a length up to max_length.
# Each chunk is joined back into a string of words and yielded as a separate chunk, so the function can handle long text by generating smaller text segments.

def chunk_text(text, max_length):
    words = text.split()
    for i in range(0, len(words), max_length):
        yield ' '.join(words[i:i + max_length])

# This function tokenizes each chunk produced by chunk_text and prepares them for input into the model.

def tokenize_and_segment(example, max_length=128):
    chunks = list(chunk_text(example['text'], max_length))
    tokenized_chunks = [tokenizer(chunk, truncation=True, max_length=max_length, padding='max_length') for chunk in chunks]

    input_ids = [tokenized_chunk['input_ids'] for tokenized_chunk in tokenized_chunks]
    attention_mask = [tokenized_chunk['attention_mask'] for tokenized_chunk in tokenized_chunks]
    # Replicates the label for each chunk of the text, ensuring each segment has the same label.
    labels = [example['label']] * len(chunks)

    return {
        'input_ids': input_ids,
        'attention_mask': attention_mask,
        'labels': labels
    }

from datasets import Dataset, DatasetDict
import itertools

max_length = 128  # Set to model's max length or a smaller value

# Preprocess a dataset by segmenting and tokenizing long text sequences, then flattens these segmented chunks into a new dataset ready for training or evaluation.
def preprocess_dataset(dataset):
    # Apply the tokenization and segmentation function to each example in the dataset
    # tokenized_examples: The map function applies tokenize_and_segment to each example in dataset.
    # Setting batched=False ensures tokenize_and_segment is applied to each example independently.
    # The result is a new dataset (tokenized_examples) where each text example has been broken into tokenized chunks, each with fields input_ids, attention_mask, and labels.
    tokenized_examples = dataset.map(lambda x: tokenize_and_segment(x, max_length), batched=False)

    # Flatten the tokenized chunks into a single dataset
    # Flattening with itertools.chain.from_iterable: This operation takes the lists of tokenized chunks (nested lists) and flattens them into a single list for each field.
    # For example, if the dataset contains three examples, each split into multiple chunks, input_ids will become one list of all chunked input_ids from the entire dataset.
    input_ids = list(itertools.chain.from_iterable(tokenized_examples['input_ids']))
    attention_mask = list(itertools.chain.from_iterable(tokenized_examples['attention_mask']))
    labels = list(itertools.chain.from_iterable(tokenized_examples['labels']))

    # Create a new dataset from the tokenized chunks and labels
    # Each row of chunked_dataset now corresponds to a single chunk (with input_ids, attention_mask, and labels), regardless of which original example it came from.
    chunked_dataset = Dataset.from_dict({
        'input_ids': input_ids,
        'attention_mask': attention_mask,
        'labels': labels
    })

    return chunked_dataset

# Apply the preprocessing to both train and validation datasets
chunked_train_dataset = preprocess_dataset(remapped_dataset['train'])
chunked_validation_dataset = preprocess_dataset(remapped_dataset['validation'])

from sklearn.metrics import ConfusionMatrixDisplay, confusion_matrix
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

def plot_confusion_matrix(y_pred, y_true, labels):
    # Compute confusion matrix and normalize it
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)
    # axis=1 specifies that the summation should happen along each row (i.e., across columns).
    cm_normalized = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]

    # Display the normalized confusion matrix with values between 0 and 1
    disp = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix=cm_normalized, display_labels=labels)
    disp.plot(cmap="Blues", values_format=".2f")  # Display with two decimal places
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)  # Rotate x-axis labels if needed
    plt.title("Normalized Confusion Matrix (Proportions)")
    plt.show()

Test accuracy is 0.71.¶

Accuracy from Method 2: Fine-tune a transformer model by segmenting the text is slightly worse than Method 1's 0.72.¶

Using overlapping chunks in Method 2 will likely improve accuracy by preserving more context across segments and enhancing prediction consistency. However, I should be mindful of the computational trade-offs.¶

The segmentation approach used in Method 2 is a fixed-length segmentation with non-overlapping chunks. Here’s how it works:¶

Fixed Length: Each segment (chunk) is created by splitting the document into consecutive sequences of words, each up to a specified maximum length (max_length).

Non-Overlapping Chunks: The chunk_text function iterates over the text in steps of max_length words without any overlap. Each chunk is independent and does not share content with adjacent chunks.

Consistent Labeling: Each chunk inherits the original document’s label, ensuring all segments reflect the document’s classification.

This approach allows for efficient processing of long documents by breaking them down into manageable, non-overlapping segments, each fitting within the model's input constraints. This segmentation method is particularly useful when overlap is not needed to maintain context between segments.

Production-Ready Post-Processing for Document Classification with Segmentation¶

To deploy the segmentation model (Method 2) effectively, a structured approach for aggregating segment predictions is needed to classify entire documents accurately. Here’s an outline:

Post-Processing Workflow:¶

  1. Segment and Predict:

    • Segment: For each incoming document, segment it using the same tokenizer, max_length and other settings as during training.
    • Predict: Pass each segment through the model to generate prediction scores for each class.

  2. Aggregate Predictions:

    • Majority Voting: Assign the document to the most frequently predicted class across segments. This is simple and effective for clear-cut classes.
    • Probability Averaging: Average the model’s softmax probabilities across segments and select the class with the highest mean probability. This approach leverages model confidence in each segment’s prediction.

  3. Optional Thresholding:

    • Confidence Threshold: Set a threshold for prediction confidence; if the highest averaged probability is too low, flag the document for human review.

  4. Edge Case Handling:

    • Single-Segment Documents: For short documents that fit in one segment, use the segment’s prediction as the document’s prediction.
    • Varied Segment Predictions: If segment predictions vary widely, flag for review, as this may indicate multiple topics or crucial content split by segmentation.

Production Considerations:¶

  • Optimize for Performance: Segmenting large documents can be computationally expensive, so ensure efficiency in processing.
  • Monitor and Log: Track model performance in production and log cases that require manual review.
  • Feedback Loop: Feed manually reviewed cases back into training to continuously refine and improve the model.

By implementing these steps, we ensure that the segmentation model not only performs well in tests but also functions reliably and accurately in real-world applications.
